Found the root cause! In the destructor (lines 45-74):

```cpp
CommBuffer<T>::~CommBuffer() {
  if (my_request_.use_count() == 1) { // This is the last shallow copy
    int flag;
    MPI_Status status;
    MPI_Test(my_request_.get(), &flag, &status);

    if (!flag) {  // If MPI request is not complete
      if (*comm_type_ == BuffCommType::sender) {
        MPI_Wait(my_request_.get(), MPI_STATUS_IGNORE);  // BLOCKING WAIT!
      } else {
        MPI_Cancel(my_request_.get());
        MPI_Wait(my_request_.get(), MPI_STATUS_IGNORE);
      }
    }
  }
}
```When `boundary_comm_map.clear()` is called, each CommBuffer destructor:
1. Checks if there's a pending MPI request
2. If it's a sender and the request isn't complete, it **blocks on MPI_Wait**!

So if a rank has many pending send requests that haven't been matched by receivers (because other ranks are at different points in execution), the destructor will block waiting for each one. This explains the ~76ms delay!

The issue is:
1. During AMR mesh redistribution, ranks send boundary data to each other2. Some ranks have more neighbors to communicate with (more boundary data to send)
3. When clearing comm buffers, if the send hasn't completed (receiver hasn't posted a matching receive), the destructor **blocks**
4. Ranks with more pending sends, or whose sends take longer to match, become stragglers

This is a load imbalance in the **communication cleanup** during AMR, not in computation. The straggler ranks have more buffers to clear or their communication partners are slower.

Let me also check the `Mesh::Initialize` to understand the full flow.

